cs.ET, cs.NE, cs.CE, cs.SY, cs.RO

The paper discusses the possibility of using plants as computing devices, which involves the intersection of several fields such as electronic engineering, computer science, and biology. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.ET (Emerging Technologies), which covers new and unconventional computing technologies. The paper also discusses the use of analog electrical computation with plants, which falls under the category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper discusses the modification of biophysical properties of plants to make them organic electronic devices, which falls under the category of cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science). The paper also discusses the interaction of roots and the implementation of computation through gradients of attractants and repellents, which falls under the category of cs.SY (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper discusses the possible designs and prototypes of computing systems based on morphological development of roots, which falls under the category of cs.RO (Robotics).
